##Q2. Notice that the first row corresponds to the whole State of Tennessee. Remove this row and save the result back to districts.

districts <- districts %>% 
  slice(-(1))
districts

##Q3. How many districts have a proficiency rate of at least 80% for both alg_1 and eng_1? #13 districts

  filter (districts, alg_1 >= 80 & eng_1 >= 80) %>% 
  count()

#what are the districts?

 filter (districts, alg_1 >= 80 & eng_1 >= 80)

##Q4. How many districts have a proviciency rate less than 50% for either alg_1 or eng_1? #8 districts

filter(districts, alg_1<50 | eng_1 <50) %>% 
  count()

#What are these districts?

filter(districts, alg_1<50 | eng_1 <50)

##Q5. Which district has the lowest graduation rate? #Tenn School for Blind

aggregate(system_name ~ grad, districts, function(grad) min(grad))

##Q6. Which district has the highest dropout rate? #Achievement School District

aggregate(system_name ~ dropout, districts, function(dropout) max(dropout))

##Q7. Within the Mid Cumberland region, which district has the highest ACT composite?

districts %>% 
  filter (districts, region == 'Mid Cumberland') %>% 
  summarise(max(act_composite))
midcumberland <- districts %>% 
  select(districts, factor_region== 'Mid Cumberland')

#What might be wrong with using just the regular mean to assess average graduation rates? #Some districts have a higher graduation rate than the others.

##Q13.Redo the previous question but use a weighted average (weighted.mean) graduation across all districts, weighing by enrollment. How much does this change your answer? Can you explain using the data the reason for the big change from using the mean? #87.28%

enroll_grad <- districts %>% 
  select (enrollment, grad) %>% 
  na.omit()
  weighted.mean(enroll_grad$grad, enroll_grad$enrollment)
[1] 87.28671

##Q16. Find the weighted average of graduation rates by region using enrollment as weights. Compare the results you get for the weighted average to what you see from the boxplots. Can you explain any discrepancy?

enroll_grad_region<- districts %>% 
  select (grad, enrollment, region) %>% 
  na.omit()
  enroll_grad_region %>% 
  group_by(region) %>% 
  summarise(weighted_grad=weighted.mean(grad, enrollment)) %>% 
  arrange(weighted_grad)

#Which school had the largest drop from alg_1 to alg_2? #Pickett County

alg1_2 <- districts %>% 
  select ('system_name', 'alg_1', 'alg_2') %>% 
  na.omit() %>% 
  mutate(alg_diff=alg_1-alg_2) %>% 
  arrange(alg_diff) %>% 
  data.frame()
alg1_2

#For what percentage of schools is it true that alg_2 is larger than alg_1? #in 18 schools (about 12%), it is true that alg_2 is larger than alg_1

districts%>%
  mutate (alg_2>alg_1) 
districts%>%
  filter ( alg_2>alg_1) %>% 
  count()
districts%>%
  filter ( alg_2>alg_1) %>% 
  count()/144 *100

#Is there a similar dropoff for eng_2 and eng_3? #There is only 1 school in which eng_3 is larger than eng_2

eng2_3<- districts %>% 
  select ('system_name', 'eng_2', 'eng_3') %>% 
  na.omit() %>% 
mutate (eng_diff= eng_3-eng_2) %>% 
  arrange (eng_diff) %>% 
  data.frame()
eng2_3
districts %>% 
  filter (eng_3>eng_2) %>% 
count()
